I use the methods `span` and `spanAll` in a several of my projects. They might come in handy for other developers too.

`span` is equivalent to `[take(...), drop(...)]` and is available in several functional programming libraries. For example, it's named [span](http://www.scala-lang.org/api/2.9.1/scala/collection/immutable/List.html#span) in Scala, and [split-with](http://clojuredocs.org/clojure_core/clojure.core/split-with) in clojure.

`spanAll` is equivalent to recursively calling span on the tail of the array. You can think of it as groupBy, but preserving order.

Here's an example use case of `spanAll`. Suppose you have a list of chat messages. When a user sends multiple chat messages in a row, you want to combine them so only show her avatar once next to the group. To do this, call `spanAll` with a function returning the sender's user id.

```
// a horrible conversation
var messages = [
    {userId:1234, msg:"hyah!"},
    {userId:4321, msg:"hey"},
    {userId:1234, msg:"we should, like, date"},
    {userId:1234, msg:"you want to see les mis?"},
    {userId:4321, msg:"sure"}];

var grouped = _.spanAll(messages, function(msg) { return msg.userId; });
/* grouped => [
 *      [{userId:1234, msg:"hyah!"}],
 *      [{userId:4321, msg:"hey"}],
 *      [{userId:1234, msg:"we should, like, date"}, {userId:1234, msg:"you want to see les mis?"}],
 *      [{userId:4321, msg:"sure"}]
 *  ];
 */
```

The following implementations of span and spanAll seek to reduce the number of calls to the supplied function:

```
/**
 * Splits the array where the function's return value changes.
 * <p>
 * When fn has no side-effects, this is equivalent to following code, but may
 * be implemented more efficiently:
 * <pre>
 *  var first = fn(head(array));
 *  var F = function (x) { return fn(x) !== first; };
 *  [take(array, F), drop(array, F)];
 * </code> )
 */
function span(array, fn, thisArg) {
    if (array.length == 0) return [[],[]]

    var callback = createCallback(fn, thisArg);
    var first = callback(array[0]);
    var unlikeFirst = 1;
    forEach(array, function(x, i) {
        if (i === 0) return;
        if (first !== callback(x)) {
            unlikeFirst = i;
            return false;
        }
    });

    var head = array.slice(0, unlikeFirst);
    var tail = array.slice(unlikeFirst, array.length);

    return [head, tail];
}

/**
 * Splits the array into sections where the return value of fn changes.
 * <p>
 * This is similar to groupby but preserves the order of the elements in the
 * array.
 * <p>
 * When fn has no side-effects, this is equivalent to the following loop, but
 * may be implemented more efficiently:
 * <pre>
 *   var accum = [], cur = array, head, tmp;
 *   while (cur.length !== 0) {
 *     tmp = _.span(cur, fn, thisArg);
 *     accum.push(tmp[0]);
 *     cur = tmp[1];
 *   }
 *   return accum;
 * </pre>
 */
function spanAll(array, fn, thisArg) {
    if (array.length === 0) return [];

    var callback = createCallback(fn, thisArg);
    var lastKey = {/*unique object*/}, startIndex = 0, result = [];

    forEach(array, function (value, index) {
        var key = callback(value, index, array);
        if (lastKey === key)
            return;
        if (index !== 0)
            result.push(array.slice(startIndex, index));
        lastKey = key;
        startIndex = index;
    });
    result.push(array.slice(startIndex, array.length));
    return result;
}
```

