Here is a feature request for another configuration setting for templates that lets you define bound arguments to templates, effectively bringing additional things into scope within the template.

``` js
_.templateSettings.extras = {
  str: helpers.strings,
  img: helpers.images
};
```

You would then essentially do something like this:

``` js
var extraKeys = _.keys(_.templateSettings.extras);
source = 'function(' + extraKeys.concat(variable).join(',') + ') {\n'
...
var extraValues = _.map(extraKeys, function (key) { 
  return _.templateSettings.extras[key]; 
});
result = Function('_', 'return ' + source + sourceURL)(lodash);
result = _.partial.apply(null, [result].concat(extraValues));
```

And now `str` and `img` would be within the scope of all templates. This is especially helpful when you are loading templates in an amd settings where it can be very difficult to `require` extra template helpers.

`_.extract(object, string)` 

Uses the string as a path finder inside the object to retrieve the specified item
Returns `undefined` if anything went wrong in finding the item.

I have come across this problem multiple times to warrant writing my own method to handle this. Feels like more people could use this if it is available in lodash.

My current implementation looks similar to the first answer here: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/6491463/accessing-nested-javascript-objects-with-string-key

Example:

``` js
var obj = {
  user: {
    order: {
      address : {
        city: 'Bangalore'
      }
    }
  }
};

 _.extract(obj, 'user.order.address.city');
// => 'Bangalore'

_.extract(obj, 'user.home.address.city');
// => undefined
```

Update: changing to `at`

Example:

``` javascript
var source = [ 'a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e', 'f', 'g' ];
_.at( source, [1, 3] );
// => [ 'b', 'd' ]

var collection = [ 
  { name: 'John', github: 'jdalton' },
  { name: 'Mathias', github: 'mathiasbynens' },
  { name: 'Kit', github:  'kitcambridge' }
];
_.at( collection, [0, 2] );
// => [ 
//       { name: 'John', github: 'jdalton' }, 
//       { name: 'Kit', github:  'kitcambridge' } 
//   ];
// (sorry Mathias)
```
### What This Does

Gives you a new array of elements from the array/collection matching the indexes provided. 
### Why I Made This

I've had this come up a few times in applications, namely when using collections as a data-source. In my latest situation, I have a collection that is the data-source for a slick-grid. When getting the selected rows, an array of which rows (e.g., `[3,5,6,7,9]`) is returned. Since lodash has so many other convenient methods to access arrays and collections, this seemed quite sensible to be able to `_.at( collection, rows )`. 

I also think some nifty stuff could be done by combining _.range with this.
